    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/precursor-mass-filtering/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MS2Query optimises re-ranking of the best analogue or exact match at the top by using a random forest that combines five features... As input for the random forest model, MS2Query uses five different features, calculated between the query spectrum and each of the 2000 preselected library spectra. These features are Spec2Vec similarity score, query precursor m/z, precursor m/z difference, a weighted average MS2Deepscore over 10 chemically similar library molecules, and the average Tanimoto score for these 10 chemically similar library molecules.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper does use precursor m/z difference as a feature in the random forest re-ranker, but MS2Query does NOT apply precursor mass filtering as a preselection step before re-ranking. The paper explicitly states: 'In contrast to existing methods, no preselection on precursor m/z is needed.' The precursor m/z difference is used as one of five input features to the random forest, not as a filtering threshold. The card's framing of 'filtering' by mass tolerance is misleading\u2014MS2Query integrates precursor m/z as a feature without applying hard mass tolerance cutoffs.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-37446-4",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "precursor-mass-filtering",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Filter MS/MS spectral library matches by precursor mass tolerance to distinguish exact matches from structural analogues and reduce false positives. This skill is essential when ranking candidate library spectra retrieved via MS2Deepscore similarity to ensure only plausible precu",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:42:24.961218+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/precursor-mass-filtering/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MS2Query optimises re-ranking of the best analogue or exact match at the top by using a random forest that combines five features... precursor m/z difference... The random forest model was trained to predict Tanimoto scores (molecular fingerprint-based chemical similarity) based on these 5 features.",
      "asbval:note": "MS2Query does integrate precursor m/z difference as a feature input to the random forest re-ranker (correct), but the card's description of 'precursor mass filtering' is misleading. MS2Query does not apply hard precursor mass tolerance filtering; instead, it uses precursor m/z difference as a soft feature in the re-ranking model. The paper states 'no preselection on precursor m/z is needed,' which contradicts the card's framing of filtering.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-37446-4",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "precursor-mass-filtering",
