    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/precursor-mass-filtering/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MS2Query searches for both exact matches and analogues in a reference library. First, potential candidates are selected based on MS2Deepscore, followed by re-ranking the spectra by using a random forest model... The test set for searching for exact matches ('exact matches test set') contains spectra that have at least one spectrum in the library from exactly the same molecule. The test set to test the performance for an analogue search ('analogues test set') contains spectra that do not have an exact match to a library spectrum.",
      "asbval:note": "MS2Query does distinguish between exact matches and analogues, but not via hard precursor mass filtering. The paper explicitly states 'no preselection on precursor m/z is needed,' meaning MS2Query does not filter out large precursor mass deviations before re-ranking. Instead, precursor m/z difference is one of five features used by the random forest to rank candidates. The card's description of filtering by mass tolerance is not how MS2Query actually works.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-37446-4",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "precursor-mass-filtering",
