    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-intensity-normalisation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The test spectra were matched against a library of 302,514 spectra... The dataset was first cleaned using matchms. The metadata was cleaned to get a uniform format and to remove or correct misplaced metadata. The dataset is split into positive and negative mode spectra. The intensities of the mass fragmentation peaks are normalised.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper does normalize intensities and process spectra in MGF format (passage 12 mentions 'MGF file'), but normalization occurs as part of library data cleaning, not as a separate preprocessing step for query spectra before MS2Query. The card's framing of 'prior to MS2Query library matching' is not explicitly supported; the paper normalizes library spectra during preparation, not query spectra as a distinct preprocessing step.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-37446-4",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-intensity-normalisation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when processing raw MS/MS spectra (in MGF, mzML, mzXML, JSON, or MSP format) prior to MS2Query library matching or MS2Deepscore embedding calculation.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:43:58.347732+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-intensity-normalisation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "These consensus spectra were taken as input for MS2Query... the spectra were uploaded on GNPS to run MSCluster to create consensus spectra.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper does use GNPS preprocessing (MSCluster for consensus spectra) before MS2Query, but does not explicitly state whether GNPS output includes normalization. The card's claim about GNPS preprocessing is plausible but not directly confirmed in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-37446-4",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-intensity-normalisation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope - When NOT to use",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input spectra are already normalized or pre-processed by an upstream tool (e.g., GNPS or MZmine output already includes normalization).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T21:43:58.347732+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-candidate-ranking/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MS2Query optimises re-ranking of the best analogue or exact match at the top by using a random forest that combines five features... As input for the random forest model, MS2Query uses 5 different features, calculated between the query spectrum and each of the 2000 preselected library spectra. These features are Spec2Vec similarity score, query precursor m/z, precursor m/z difference, a weighted average MS2Deepscore over 10 chemically similar library molecules, and the average Tanimoto score for these 10 chemically most similar library molecules.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper does combine structural similarity and spectral neighbourhood density via random forest, but the five features used are: (1) Spec2Vec similarity, (2) query precursor m/z, (3) precursor m/z difference, (4) average MS2Deepscore over 10 chemically similar library molecules, and (5) average Tanimoto score for those 10 molecules. The card claims 'InChIKey score' as a feature, but the paper uses Tanimoto score (molecular fingerprint-based chemical similarity) and does not explicitly name InChIKey as a direct input feature to the random forest. The 'spectral neighbourhood density' concept aligns with feature 4 (average MS2Deepscore of multiple library molecules), but the card's terminology differs from the paper's actual feature set.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-37446-4",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
