    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-candidate-ranking/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MS2Query optimises re-ranking of the best analogue or exact match at the top by using a random forest that combines five features... The random forest model was trained to predict Tanimoto scores (molecular fingerprint-based chemical similarity) based on these 5 features.",
      "asbval:note": "MS2Query does orchestrate the re-ranking via random forest, but the card claims it combines 'InChIKey and neighbourhood scores' specifically. The paper states the five features are: Spec2Vec similarity, query precursor m/z, precursor m/z difference, average MS2Deepscore over 10 chemically similar library molecules, and average Tanimoto score. The model is trained to predict Tanimoto scores (not InChIKey scores). The 'neighbourhood density' concept is present (feature 4), but 'InChIKey score' is not explicitly named as a feature.",
